[3]
Date: Fri 1 Nov 2002 11:54:11 -0000
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source ABC news online, 1 Nov 2002 [edited]
<http://abc.net.au/news/newsitems/s716958.htm>

Health authorities confirm two more malaria cases
-------------------------------------------------------
In far north Queensland 2 more cases of locally-acquired malaria have been
confirmed by health officials. Yesterday 3 cases were reported in the
first outbreak of the disease on Queensland's northern mainland since 1986.
Dr Jeffrey Hanna, from the Tropical Public Health Unit, says it is believed
all 5 patients caught the disease from mosquito bites while camping at a
beach near Mossman early last month.
Dr Hanna says there is little risk of malaria spreading into the wider
community."The mosquitos that were infectious earlier in October 2002 would
have died off by now just through natural attrition," he said."To have
another generation of cases we'd need some people living there to act as
reservoirs and because the nature of the campsite is people don't stay
there more than a couple of nights."
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This outbreak is very similar to the cases of malaria that occurred
recently in Virginia as cited below. In both cases the presumed source was
some one who was from or had traveled in a foreign country. In this case a
specific individual is suspected as the initial source, as he was ill with
subsequently diagnosed malaria. In the Virginia outbreak there was no
obvious initial source; however, travellers from _Plasmodium vivax_-endemic
countries may carry gametocytes in their blood for weeks and if immune may
be completely asymptomatic. An appropriate vector mosquito can transmit the
disease to others. - Mod.DK]
